SIMPLE: precise
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precise
<hw>Pre*cise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praecisus</ets> cut off, brief, concise, p. p. of
<ets>praecidere</ets> to cut off in front, to cut off; <ets>prae</ets>
before + <ets>caedere</ets> to cut: cf. F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧cis</ets>. Cf.
<er>Concise</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having determinate
limitations; exactly or sharply defined or stated; definite; exact;
nice; not vague or equivocal; <as>as, <ex>precise</ex> rules of
morality</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law in this point is not <qex>precise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the hour <qex>precise</qex>⟦br⟧
Exacts our parting hence.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Strictly adhering or conforming to rule; very nice
or exact; punctilious in conduct or ceremony; formal; ceremonious.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was ever <qex>precise</qex> in promise-keeping.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Accurate; exact; definite; correct; scrupulous;
punctilious; particular; nice; formal. See <er>Accurate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pre*cise"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pre*cise"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precisian</ent>⟦br⟧
